An Italian transportation company needs to move some empty containers from its 6 warehouses (located in Verona, Perugia, Rome, Pescara, Taranto, and Lamezia) to major national ports (Genoa, Venice, Ancona, Naples, Bari). The container inventory at the warehouses is as follows:

|  | Empty Containers |
|:---:|:---:|
| Verona | 10 |
| Perugia | 12 |
| Rome | 20 |
| Pescara | 24 |
| Taranto | 18 |
| Lamezia | 40 |

The demand at the ports is as follows:

|  | Container Demand |
|:---:|:---:|
| Genoa | 20 |
| Venice | 15 |
| Ancona | 25 |
| Naples | 33 |
| Bari | 21 |

The transport is carried out by a fleet of trucks. The cost to transport each container is proportional to the distance traveled by the trucks, with a rate of 30 euros per kilometer. Each truck can carry up to 2 containers. The distances are as follows:

|  | Genoa | Venice | Ancona | Naples | Bari |
|:---:|:---:|:---:|:---:|:---:|:---:|
| Verona | $290 \mathrm{~km}$ | $115 \mathrm{~km}$ | $355 \mathrm{~km}$ | $715 \mathrm{~km}$ | $810 \mathrm{~km}$ |
| Perugia | $380 \mathrm{~km}$ | $340 \mathrm{~km}$ | $165 \mathrm{~km}$ | $380 \mathrm{~km}$ | $610 \mathrm{~km}$ |
| Rome | $505 \mathrm{~km}$ | $530 \mathrm{~km}$ | $285 \mathrm{~km}$ | $220 \mathrm{~km}$ | $450 \mathrm{~km}$ |
| Pescara | $655 \mathrm{~km}$ | $450 \mathrm{~km}$ | $155 \mathrm{~km}$ | $240 \mathrm{~km}$ | $315 \mathrm{~km}$ |
| Taranto | $1010 \mathrm{~km}$ | $840 \mathrm{~km}$ | $550 \mathrm{~km}$ | $305 \mathrm{~km}$ | $95 \mathrm{~km}$ |
| Lamezia | $1072 \mathrm{~km}$ | $1097 \mathrm{~km}$ | $747 \mathrm{~km}$ | $372 \mathrm{~km}$ | $333 \mathrm{~km}$ |

Write a mathematical program to find the minimum cost transportation policy and solve it using COPTPY.
-------------
【数学模型】:
 ### Sets

- \( I \): set of warehouses  
  \( I = \{\text{Verona (V)}, \text{Perugia (Pe)}, \text{Rome (R)}, \text{Pescara (Ps)}, \text{Taranto (T)}, \text{Lamezia (L)}\} \)

- \( J \): set of ports  
  \( J = \{\text{Genoa (G)}, \text{Venice (Ve)}, \text{Ancona (A)}, \text{Naples (N)}, \text{Bari (B)}\} \)

---

### Parameters

- Supply at warehouse \( i \in I \):  
  \[
  s_i
  \]
\[
\begin{aligned}
&s_V=10,\; s_{Pe}=12,\; s_R=20,\; s_{Ps}=24,\; s_T=18,\; s_L=40
\end{aligned}
\]

- Demand at port \( j \in J \):  
  \[
  d_j
  \]
\[
\begin{aligned}
&d_G=20,\; d_{Ve}=15,\; d_A=25,\; d_N=33,\; d_B=21
\end{aligned}
\]

- Distance (km) from warehouse \( i \) to port \( j \):  
  \[
  \text{dist}_{ij}
  \]

- Transportation cost per container:

Each truck carries at most 2 containers and costs \(30\) €/km.  
Thus cost per container per km:

\[
c^{unit} = \frac{30}{2} = 15 \text{ €/km}
\]

So per-container cost:

\[
c_{ij} = 15 \cdot \text{dist}_{ij}
\]

---

### Decision Variables

\[
x_{ij} \ge 0
\]

Number of containers transported from warehouse \( i \in I \) to port \( j \in J \).

---

### Objective Function

Minimize total transportation cost:

\[
\min Z = \sum_{i \in I} \sum_{j \in J} c_{ij} x_{ij}
\]

i.e.,

\[
\min Z = \sum_{i \in I} \sum_{j \in J} 15 \cdot \text{dist}_{ij} \, x_{ij}
\]

---

### Constraints

#### 1. Supply constraints (warehouse capacity)

\[
\sum_{j \in J} x_{ij} \le s_i \qquad \forall i \in I
\]

---

#### 2. Demand constraints (port requirements)

\[
\sum_{i \in I} x_{ij} = d_j \qquad \forall j \in J
\]

---

#### 3. Non-negativity

\[
x_{ij} \ge 0 \qquad \forall i \in I, j \in J
\]

---

### Complete Linear Programming Model

\[
\begin{aligned}
\min \quad & \sum_{i \in I} \sum_{j \in J} 15\,\text{dist}_{ij} \, x_{ij} \\
\text{s.t.} \quad
& \sum_{j \in J} x_{ij} \le s_i && \forall i \in I \\
& \sum_{i \in I} x_{ij} = d_j && \forall j \in J \\
& x_{ij} \ge 0 && \forall i \in I, j \in J
\end{aligned}
\]

This is a balanced transportation linear programming model suitable for implementation in COPTPY.
【验证之后的模型】:
 ### ✅ Model Check

- Total supply:  
  \(10+12+20+24+18+40 = 124\)

- Total demand:  
  \(20+15+25+33+21 = 114\)

Since **total supply > total demand**, the problem is **not balanced**.

Therefore:
- Supply constraints must be **≤** (not =).
- Or equivalently, a dummy port with demand 10 and zero cost could be added.

The previous model correctly used:

\[
\sum_{j} x_{ij} \le s_i
\]

So it is **feasible and correct**.

---

### ✅ Improvement

The modeling of transportation cost needs refinement.

The statement says:

> Each truck can carry up to 2 containers.  
> Cost = 30 €/km per truck.

If we assume:
- Trucks are fully utilized (reasonable in LP relaxation),
- Containers are divisible (standard transportation assumption),

then cost per container per km:

\[
\frac{30}{2} = 15
\]

Thus:

\[
c_{ij} = 15 \cdot \text{dist}_{ij}
\]

This is a correct linear relaxation.

✅ Therefore the model is already optimal as a linear programming formulation.

No structural correction is required.

---

# ✅ Final Mathematical Model

---

## Sets

\[
I = \{\text{Verona, Perugia, Rome, Pescara, Taranto, Lamezia}\}
\]

\[
J = \{\text{Genoa, Venice, Ancona, Naples, Bari}\}
\]

---

## Parameters

- Supply at warehouse \( i \in I \):

\[
s_i
\]

\[
(10, 12, 20, 24, 18, 40)
\]

- Demand at port \( j \in J \):

\[
d_j
\]

\[
(20, 15, 25, 33, 21)
\]

- Distance (km):

\[
\text{dist}_{ij}
\]

- Unit transportation cost per container:

\[
c_{ij} = 15 \cdot \text{dist}_{ij}
\]

---

## Decision Variables

\[
x_{ij} \ge 0
\]

Number of containers transported from warehouse \( i \) to port \( j \).

---

## Objective Function

\[
\min Z = \sum_{i \in I} \sum_{j \in J} 15\,\text{dist}_{ij}\, x_{ij}
\]

---

## Constraints

### 1. Warehouse supply constraints

\[
\sum_{j \in J} x_{ij} \le s_i
\qquad \forall i \in I
\]

---

### 2. Port demand constraints

\[
\sum_{i \in I} x_{ij} = d_j
\qquad \forall j \in J
\]

---

### 3. Non-negativity

\[
x_{ij} \ge 0
\qquad \forall i \in I,\; j \in J
\]

---

# ✅ Final Remarks

- The model is a standard **unbalanced transportation LP**.
- Linear, scalable, and directly implementable in COPTPY.
- No further structural optimization is required.
【Python Gurobi 代码】:
 ```python
import gurobipy as gp
from gurobipy import GRB

# Sets
warehouses = ["Verona", "Perugia", "Rome", "Pescara", "Taranto", "Lamezia"]
ports = ["Genoa", "Venice", "Ancona", "Naples", "Bari"]

# Supply
supply = {
    "Verona": 10,
    "Perugia": 12,
    "Rome": 20,
    "Pescara": 24,
    "Taranto": 18,
    "Lamezia": 40
}

# Demand
demand = {
    "Genoa": 20,
    "Venice": 15,
    "Ancona": 25,
    "Naples": 33,
    "Bari": 21
}

# Distances (km)
distance = {
    ("Verona", "Genoa"): 290, ("Verona", "Venice"): 115, ("Verona", "Ancona"): 355, ("Verona", "Naples"): 715, ("Verona", "Bari"): 810,
    ("Perugia", "Genoa"): 380, ("Perugia", "Venice"): 340, ("Perugia", "Ancona"): 165, ("Perugia", "Naples"): 380, ("Perugia", "Bari"): 610,
    ("Rome", "Genoa"): 505, ("Rome", "Venice"): 530, ("Rome", "Ancona"): 285, ("Rome", "Naples"): 220, ("Rome", "Bari"): 450,
    ("Pescara", "Genoa"): 655, ("Pescara", "Venice"): 450, ("Pescara", "Ancona"): 155, ("Pescara", "Naples"): 240, ("Pescara", "Bari"): 315,
    ("Taranto", "Genoa"): 1010, ("Taranto", "Venice"): 840, ("Taranto", "Ancona"): 550, ("Taranto", "Naples"): 305, ("Taranto", "Bari"): 95,
    ("Lamezia", "Genoa"): 1072, ("Lamezia", "Venice"): 1097, ("Lamezia", "Ancona"): 747, ("Lamezia", "Naples"): 372, ("Lamezia", "Bari"): 333
}

# Cost per container per km
cost_per_km = 15

# Create model
model = gp.Model("Container_Transportation")

# Decision variables
x = model.addVars(warehouses, ports, lb=0, vtype=GRB.CONTINUOUS, name="x")

# Objective function
model.setObjective(
    gp.quicksum(cost_per_km * distance[i, j] * x[i, j] for i in warehouses for j in ports),
    GRB.MINIMIZE
)

# Supply constraints
for i in warehouses:
    model.addConstr(
        gp.quicksum(x[i, j] for j in ports) <= supply[i],
        name=f"Supply_{i}"
    )

# Demand constraints
for j in ports:
    model.addConstr(
        gp.quicksum(x[i, j] for i in warehouses) == demand[j],
        name=f"Demand_{j}"
    )

# Optimize
model.optimize()

# Output results
if model.status == GRB.OPTIMAL:
    print(f"\nOptimal Total Cost: {model.objVal:.2f} euros\n")
    print("Optimal Transportation Plan (containers shipped):")
    for i in warehouses:
        for j in ports:
            if x[i, j].x > 1e-6:
                print(f"{i} -> {j}: {x[i, j].x:.2f}")
else:
    print("No optimal solution found.")
```
