A company produces two types of small motorcycles, where type A is entirely manufactured by the company, and type B is assembled from imported parts. The production, assembly, and inspection time required for each unit of these two products are shown in Table 3.2.

Table 3.2

| Type | Process | | | Selling Price <br> (Yuan/unit) |
| :---: | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| | Manufacturing | Assembly | Inspection | |
| Type A (hours/unit) | 20 | 5 | 3 | 650 |
| Type B (hours/unit) | 0 | 7 | 6 | 725 |
| Max production capacity per week (hours) | 120 | 80 | 40 | |
| Production cost per hour (Yuan) | 12 | 8 | 10 | |

If the company's operational goals and targets are as follows:

$p_{1}$ : The total profit per week should be at least 3000 yuan;

$p_{2}$ : At least 5 units of type A motorcycles should be produced per week;

$p_{3}$ : Minimize the idle time of each process as much as possible. The weight coefficients of the three processes are proportional to their hourly costs, and overtime is not allowed.

Try to establish a model for this problem.
-------------
【数学模型】:
 ### Decision Variables
\[
\begin{aligned}
x_1 & = \text{number of type A motorcycles produced per week} \\
x_2 & = \text{number of type B motorcycles produced per week}
\end{aligned}
\]

### Deviation Variables (Goal Programming)

\[
\begin{aligned}
d_1^-, d_1^+ & : \text{negative and positive deviations for profit goal} \\
d_2^-, d_2^+ & : \text{negative and positive deviations for type A production goal} \\
d_3^-, d_3^+ & : \text{deviation variables for manufacturing capacity} \\
d_4^-, d_4^+ & : \text{deviation variables for assembly capacity} \\
d_5^-, d_5^+ & : \text{deviation variables for inspection capacity}
\end{aligned}
\]

(All variables ≥ 0)

---

### 1. Profit Expression

Unit profit:

Type A:
\[
650 - (20\times12 + 5\times8 + 3\times10)
= 650 - (240 + 40 + 30)
= 340
\]

Type B:
\[
725 - (7\times8 + 6\times10)
= 725 - (56 + 60)
= 609
\]

Total weekly profit:
\[
340x_1 + 609x_2
\]

---

### Goal Constraints

#### (1) Profit Goal (≥ 3000)

\[
340x_1 + 609x_2 + d_1^- - d_1^+ = 3000
\]

(Only \(d_1^-\) is penalized)

---

#### (2) Minimum Production of Type A (≥ 5)

\[
x_1 + d_2^- - d_2^+ = 5
\]

(Only \(d_2^-\) is penalized)

---

#### (3) Capacity Goals (Idle Time Minimization)

Manufacturing (120 hours):
\[
20x_1 + d_3^- - d_3^+ = 120
\]

Assembly (80 hours):
\[
5x_1 + 7x_2 + d_4^- - d_4^+ = 80
\]

Inspection (40 hours):
\[
3x_1 + 6x_2 + d_5^- - d_5^+ = 40
\]

Since overtime is not allowed:
\[
d_3^+ = d_4^+ = d_5^+ = 0
\]

Thus only idle time deviations \(d_3^-, d_4^-, d_5^-\) exist.

---

### Objective Function (Preemptive Goal Programming)

Priority structure:

\[
p_1 \gg p_2 \gg p_3
\]

---

#### Priority 1 (Profit)

\[
\min Z_1 = d_1^-
\]

---

#### Priority 2 (Minimum Type A Production)

\[
\min Z_2 = d_2^-
\]

---

#### Priority 3 (Minimize Weighted Idle Time)

Weights proportional to hourly cost:

Manufacturing: 12  
Assembly: 8  
Inspection: 10  

\[
\min Z_3 = 12d_3^- + 8d_4^- + 10d_5^-
\]

---

### Complete Model (Preemptive Form)

Lexicographically minimize:

\[
\min \left( d_1^- ,\; d_2^- ,\; 12d_3^- + 8d_4^- + 10d_5^- \right)
\]

Subject to:

\[
\begin{aligned}
340x_1 + 609x_2 + d_1^- - d_1^+ &= 3000 \\
x_1 + d_2^- - d_2^+ &= 5 \\
20x_1 + d_3^- &= 120 \\
5x_1 + 7x_2 + d_4^- &= 80 \\
3x_1 + 6x_2 + d_5^- &= 40 \\
x_1, x_2 &\ge 0 \\
d_i^-, d_i^+ &\ge 0
\end{aligned}
\]

This is the required linear goal programming model.
