A university computer lab hires 4 undergraduates (designated 1, 2, 3, and 4) and 2 graduate students (designated 5 and 6) for duty answering questions. The maximum duty hours from Monday to Friday and the hourly wage for each person are shown in Table 5-9.

Table 5-9
| Student ID | Wage (CNY/h) | Monday | Tuesday | Wednesday | Thursday | Friday |
|------------|--------------|--------|---------|-----------|----------|--------|
| 1          | 10.0         | 6      | 0       | 6         | 0        | 7      |
| 2          | 10.0         | 0      | 6       | 0         | 6        | 0      |
| 3          | 9.9          | 4      | 8       | 3         | 0        | 5      |
| 4          | 9.8          | 5      | 5       | 6         | 0        | 4      |
| 5          | 10.8         | 3      | 0       | 4         | 8        | 0      |
| 6          | 11.3         | 0      | 6       | 0         | 6        | 3      |

The lab operates from 8:00 AM to 10:00 PM, and there must be one and only one student on duty during open hours. It is also required that each undergraduate must work at least 8 hours per week, and each graduate student must work at least 7 hours per week. Additionally, supplement the following requirements: each student can work no more than 2 shifts per week, and no more than 3 students can be scheduled for duty each day. Based on these conditions, establish a new mathematical model.
-------------
【数学模型】:
 **Sets**

- \( i = 1,\dots,6 \)  (students)  
- \( d \in D=\{Mon,Tue,Wed,Thu,Fri\} \)

**Parameters**

- \( c_i \): hourly wage of student \(i\)  
- \( a_{id} \): maximum available hours of student \(i\) on day \(d\) (from Table 5‑9)  
- \( H = 14 \): lab open hours per day (8:00–22:00)  
- \( L_i \): minimum weekly hours  
  \[
  L_i =
  \begin{cases}
  8, & i=1,2,3,4 \\
  7, & i=5,6
  \end{cases}
  \]

**Decision Variables**

- \( x_{id} \ge 0 \): hours assigned to student \(i\) on day \(d\)  
- \( y_{id} \in \{0,1\} \): 1 if student \(i\) works on day \(d\), 0 otherwise  

---

## Mathematical Model

### Objective Function
\[
\min Z = \sum_{i=1}^{6} \sum_{d \in D} c_i \, x_{id}
\]

---

### Constraints

#### 1. Daily coverage requirement (exactly one student on duty at any time)
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{6} x_{id} = H, \quad \forall d \in D
\]

---

#### 2. Availability constraints
\[
x_{id} \le a_{id} \, y_{id}, \quad \forall i,d
\]

---

#### 3. Weekly minimum working hours
\[
\sum_{d \in D} x_{id} \ge L_i, \quad \forall i=1,\dots,6
\]

---

#### 4. Each student works at most 2 shifts per week
\[
\sum_{d \in D} y_{id} \le 2, \quad \forall i
\]

---

#### 5. No more than 3 students scheduled per day
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{6} y_{id} \le 3, \quad \forall d \in D
\]

---

#### 6. Variable domains
\[
x_{id} \ge 0, \quad y_{id} \in \{0,1\}
\]

---

This formulation constitutes the required mixed-integer linear programming (MILP) model.
【验证之后的模型】:
 The original model is **not fully consistent** with the problem statement.

### Issue

The statement says:

> “there must be **one and only one student on duty during open hours (8:00–22:00)**”

This means **exactly one student must cover each day**, i.e., a single student works the full 14-hour shift of that day.

However, the previous formulation allowed:
- Multiple students per day  
- Fractional hour splitting  
- A constraint “no more than 3 students per day,” which contradicts “one and only one student”

Therefore, the model must be corrected so that:
- Exactly one student is assigned per day  
- That student works the full 14 hours  
- The “≤ 3 students per day” constraint becomes redundant and must be removed  

---

# ✅ Corrected and Optimized Mathematical Model

---

## Sets

- \( i = 1,\dots,6 \)  (students)  
- \( d \in D=\{Mon,Tue,Wed,Thu,Fri\} \)

---

## Parameters

- \( c_i \): hourly wage of student \(i\)  
- \( a_{id} \): maximum available hours of student \(i\) on day \(d\)  
- \( H = 14 \): required working hours per day  
- Weekly minimum hours:

\[
L_i =
\begin{cases}
8, & i=1,2,3,4 \\
7, & i=5,6
\end{cases}
\]

---

## Decision Variables

\[
y_{id} =
\begin{cases}
1, & \text{if student } i \text{ is assigned to day } d \\
0, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

---

## Objective Function

Since one assigned student works all 14 hours:

\[
\min Z = \sum_{i=1}^{6} \sum_{d \in D} 14\, c_i \, y_{id}
\]

---

## Constraints

### 1. Exactly one student per day

\[
\sum_{i=1}^{6} y_{id} = 1, 
\quad \forall d \in D
\]

---

### 2. Availability feasibility

A student can only be assigned if available for at least 14 hours that day:

\[
14\, y_{id} \le a_{id}, 
\quad \forall i,d
\]

(If \(a_{id} < 14\), then \(y_{id}=0\))

---

### 3. Weekly minimum working hours

Since each assignment gives 14 hours:

\[
14 \sum_{d \in D} y_{id} \ge L_i,
\quad \forall i
\]

---

### 4. Each student works at most 2 shifts per week

\[
\sum_{d \in D} y_{id} \le 2,
\quad \forall i
\]

---

### 5. Binary restriction

\[
y_{id} \in \{0,1\}
\]

---

# ✅ Final Model Characteristics

- Pure 0–1 integer programming model  
- Simpler than previous formulation  
- No redundant constraints  
- Fully consistent with:
  - Exactly one student per day  
  - Weekly minimum hours  
  - At most 2 shifts per week  
  - Availability limits  

